TARGET {
  output: "Conflict resolution between two values for the same field"
  lang: JSON
  profile: data
}

TOKENS {
  escalateThreshold: 0.5
}

RUNTIME_INPUTS {
  | name              | type   | description                                          |
  |-------------------|--------|------------------------------------------------------|
  | field_name        | string | The field with conflicting values                    |
  | new_value         | any    | The value from the newly extracted entity            |
  | existing_value    | any    | The value currently in the data cube                 |
  | new_source        | object | Source metadata for the new value                    |
  | existing_source   | object | Source metadata for the existing value                |
  | entity_type       | string | The entity type this conflict occurs on              |
  | trust_memory      | string | Agent's learned trust hierarchy from memory          |
}

BEHAVIOR ResolveConflict {
  Two sources disagree on the same field. You must resolve or escalate.

  STEP 1 — Assess the conflict.
    Are the values actually different, or just differently formatted?
    "$4,200" and "4200" and "4200.00" are the same value.
    "John Smith" and "J. Smith" might be the same person.
    If values are equivalent after normalization, return resolution "equivalent".

  STEP 2 — Check trust_memory.
    The agent may have learned which sources are more reliable for which fields.
    "Source A is authoritative for amounts" → Source A wins on amount conflicts.
    "Source B has stale data" → Source B loses.
    If trust_memory has guidance, follow it.

  STEP 3 — Apply resolution strategies (in order):
    1. Trust hierarchy from memory (if available)
    2. Recency — more recent extraction wins (check source.extracted_at)
    3. Specificity — more detailed/complete value wins
    4. Escalate — if none of the above resolves it

  STEP 4 — Score confidence in resolution.
    High (0.8+): Trust hierarchy explicitly covers this case
    Medium (0.5-0.79): Recency or specificity provides a reasonable answer
    Low (<0.5): MUST escalate — don't resolve when unsure
}

CONSTRAINT {
  MUST check for format equivalence before declaring a real conflict
  MUST check trust_memory before applying default strategies
  MUST escalate if confidence is below escalateThreshold
  MUST preserve BOTH values in the output (winner and loser)
  MUST NOT silently discard any value
  MUST state the resolution strategy used
}

CHECKLIST {
  [ ] Format equivalence checked first
  [ ] trust_memory consulted before default strategies
  [ ] Both values preserved in output
  [ ] Resolution strategy explicitly stated
  [ ] Confidence below escalateThreshold triggers escalation
  [ ] Reasoning explains WHY one value wins
}

FORMAT {
  OUTPUT: {
    "resolution": "new_wins | existing_wins | equivalent | escalate",
    "winning_value": "<the value to keep>",
    "losing_value": "<the value to demote>",
    "confidence": <number>,
    "strategy": "<which strategy resolved it>",
    "reasoning": "<why this resolution>"
  }
}
